  "prompt": "What evidence can be provided by India to prove the claimed surgical strikes in PoK?",
  "response": "The surgical strikes conducted by India in Pakistan-occupied Kashmir (PoK) in September 2016 have been a subject of significant debate and interest. India has claimed that these strikes targeted terrorist launch pads across the Line of Control (LoC). To substantiate its claims, India has provided various forms of evidence and statements, though not all details have been publicly disclosed. Here are some of the types of evidence and methods that could be utilized to substantiate such claims:\n\n1. **Military Briefings**: The Indian Army held a press conference shortly after the strikes, providing an official narrative of the operations and affirming their success.\n\n2. **Satellite Imagery**: Classified satellite images or reconnaissance data, though not made publicly available, could be used to show before-and-after conditions of the targeted sites.\n\n3. **Video Footage**: Reports have suggested that video footage of the operation was recorded via drones or other surveillance methods. While such footage has not been publicly released, it serves as a form of evidence.\n\n4. **Statements from Officials**: High-level Indian officials, including those from the Ministry of External Affairs and the military, have consistently asserted that the strikes occurred and were successful.\n\n5. **Testimonies**: Accounts from military personnel involved in the operation could serve as direct testimony, although such details are usually kept confidential for security reasons.\n\n6. **Diplomatic Briefings**: Indian officials briefed various foreign diplomats and officials about the operations, indicating confidence in the veracity of their claims.\n\n7. **Operational Details**: While much of this remains classified, broad outlines of the operation, such as planning and execution strategy, were provided to add weight to the claims.\n\nThough these forms of evidence have been asserted, much of what can substantiate the claims remains classified due to the sensitive nature of the operation and security concerns. The lack of publicly released evidence has led to skepticism and varying interpretations internationally and domestically.",
